<div class="bg-zinc-950 text-zinc-100">
  <.marketing_nav current={:docs} />

  <section class="py-16 sm:py-24">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-6 lg:px-8">
      <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-indigo-400">Use cases / Cassandra</p>
      <h1 class="mt-2 text-4xl font-bold tracking-tight text-zinc-50 md:text-5xl">
        Letting an LLM run nodetool — safely
      </h1>
      <p class="mt-6 text-lg leading-8 text-zinc-400">
        On a Cassandra cluster, "agent runs <code>nodetool repair</code>" is a
        coin-flip between "you reduced inconsistency by 0.001%" and "you took
        an extra disk offline for six hours". This page walks the boundary.
      </p>

      <h2 class="mt-12 text-2xl font-semibold text-zinc-50">What the pack declares</h2>
      <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-zinc-400">
        The shipping <code>cassandra</code> pack (see
        <.external_link
          href="https://github.com/andrewdryga/emisar/tree/main/runner/examples/packs/cassandra"
          class="text-indigo-400 hover:text-indigo-300"
        >examples/packs/cassandra</.external_link>)
        publishes six actions:
      </p>
      <ul class="mt-4 space-y-2 text-sm text-zinc-300">
        <li>
          <code class="font-mono text-indigo-300">cassandra.nodetool_status</code> — risk:
          <code>low</code>, read-only. Cluster topology and per-node up/down state.
        </li>
        <li>
          <code class="font-mono text-indigo-300">cassandra.nodetool_compactionstats</code> — risk:
          <code>low</code>, read-only. Pending and in-flight compactions per host.
        </li>
        <li>
          <code class="font-mono text-indigo-300">cassandra.nodetool_tablestats</code> — risk:
          <code>low</code>, read-only. Per-keyspace / per-table stats (read counts, bytes, latency).
        </li>
        <li>
          <code class="font-mono text-indigo-300">cassandra.nodetool_tpstats</code> — risk:
          <code>low</code>, read-only. Thread-pool queue depth — fastest signal for a saturated node.
        </li>
        <li>
          <code class="font-mono text-indigo-300">cassandra.analyze_disk_pressure</code> — risk:
          <code>low</code>, read-only. Shell pipeline summarising disk fill per data dir.
        </li>
        <li>
          <code class="font-mono text-indigo-300">cassandra.nodetool_repair</code> — risk:
          <code>high</code>. Args restricted to an allowlist of keyspaces. Long timeout, default policy requires one human approval.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="mt-10 text-2xl font-semibold text-zinc-50">Typical triage flow</h2>
      <ol class="mt-4 space-y-3 text-sm text-zinc-300 list-decimal pl-6">
        <li>Alert fires: read latency on <code>orders_ks</code> creeps up.</li>
        <li>
          Model: <code>nodetool_status</code>. Sees node 3 is DN (down). Calls
          <code>nodetool_compactionstats</code> on its peers — pending compactions
          piling up.
        </li>
        <li>
          Model proposes <code>nodetool_repair orders_ks</code> on the surviving
          replicas. Policy says <code>require_approval</code>. The model surfaces this
          to the operator with the policy reason ("repair is high-risk; one approval
          required") and the LLM-supplied <code>reason</code> for the run.
        </li>
        <li>
          Operator gets an email. One click → approve. The repair dispatches.
          Output streams into the run detail page, hash-chained to audit.
        </li>
        <li>
          If the repair runs longer than 30m, the runner SIGTERMs the process group
          (catching the <code>nodetool</code> wrapper plus any subprocesses) and
          escalates to SIGKILL after the per-action grace period.
        </li>
      </ol>

      <h2 class="mt-10 text-2xl font-semibold text-zinc-50">What the LLM cannot do</h2>
      <ul class="mt-4 space-y-2 text-sm text-zinc-300">
        <li>
          Run <code>nodetool removenode</code>: not in the catalog. Request rejected
          at the runner before exec.
        </li>
        <li>
          Run <code>nodetool repair</code> against a keyspace not in the allowlist:
          arg validation rejects it.
        </li>
        <li>
          Bypass approval by claiming the action is "low risk": the runner publishes
          the risk from the catalog, the policy engine evaluates against the
          authoritative value, not what the caller passes.
        </li>
        <li>
          Read <code>cassandra.yaml</code>: there's no
          <code>cassandra.read_config</code> action. Read-actions for configuration
          are a separate authoring decision.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <p class="mt-10 text-sm text-zinc-400">
        See <.link href="/docs/action-packs" class="text-indigo-400 hover:text-indigo-300">the action pack reference</.link>
        for the YAML schema. To run the shipping Cassandra pack against your
        cluster, drop it under <code class="font-mono text-xs">/etc/emisar/packs/</code>
        and SIGHUP the runner.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <.marketing_footer />
</div>
